8 WORKFORCE DIPLOMA PROGRAM
9 SECTION 6.10.(a) Program; Purpose. – The Community Colleges System Office
10 shall establish the Workforce Diploma Program (Program) for the 2025-2026 and the 2026-2027
11 fiscal years. The purpose of the Program is to assist eligible students to obtain a high school
12 diploma and develop employability and career and technical skills. The System Office shall
13 contract with each qualifying third-party entity to separately administer a statewide version of
14 the Program.
15 SECTION 6.10.(b) Definitions. – For purposes of this section, the following
16 definitions shall apply:
17 (1) Eligible student. – Any adult who meets the following criteria:
18 a. Is 21 years of age or older.
19 b. Is a resident of North Carolina.
20 c. Has not earned a high school diploma or its equivalent.
21 (2) Employability skills certification. – A certificate earned by demonstrating
22 professional nontechnical skills through assessment and must include the
23 program standards of the United States Department of Labor's "Skills to Pay
24 the Bills: Mastering Soft Skills for Workplace Success."
25 (3) Half credit. – Equivalent to one course or a semester of study.
26 (4) Participant. – An eligible student who is participating in the Program.
27 (5) Qualifying third-party entity. – An entity that meets all of the following
28 requirements:
29 a. Did the following in the past five years:
30 1. Administered at least three statewide adult high school
31 diploma programs outside of the State.
32 2. For any program described in sub-sub-subdivision 1. of this
33 sub-subdivision, maintained a graduation rate of at least fifty
34 percent (50%) based on a two-year cohort beginning with the
35 second cohort of the program.
36 b. Is accredited by an external, regional accrediting agency.
37 c. Offers a course catalog that aligns with curriculum requirements for a
38 high school diploma in the State.
39 SECTION 6.10.(c) Program Requirements. – The Program shall do at least the
40 following:
41 (1) Provide one or more courses that help participants obtain a high school
42 diploma and enter or advance within a specific occupation or occupational
43 cluster. Course completion shall be competency-based.
44 (2) Assist participants in obtaining employment, including resume development
45 and mock interviews.
46 (3) Include at least the following:
47 a. Proactive communication with participants regarding their pace and
48 progress through learning plans.
49 b. A plan for courses and credits needed for each participant that
50 integrates graduation requirements and career goals.
51 c. Mentoring services.
Page 96 Senate Bill 257-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 d. Milestone tracking.
2 e. Academic skill intake assessments and transcript evaluations.
3 f. A catalog of courses necessary to meet graduation requirements.
4 g. Remediation opportunities in literacy and numeracy.
5 h. Employability skills certifications.
6 i. Preparation for workforce credentials.
7 j. Career advising services.
8 k. Access to online tutoring services at any time.
9 SECTION 6.10.(d) Allocation of Funds. – Funds shall be provided to each
10 qualifying third-party entity on a per participant basis, up to seven thousand five hundred dollars
11 ($7,500) per participant, based on the completion of milestones, as follows:
12 (1) Two hundred seventy-five dollars ($275.00) for the completion of each half
13 credit.
14 (2) Two hundred seventy-five dollars ($275.00) for the completion of an
15 employability skills certification program equivalent to one credit.
16 (3) Two hundred seventy-five dollars ($275.00) for the attainment of an
17 industry-recognized credential requiring up to 50 hours of training.
18 (4) Five hundred fifty dollars ($550.00) for the attainment of an
19 industry-recognized credential requiring between 51 and 100 hours of
20 training.
21 (5) Eight hundred twenty-five dollars ($825.00) for the attainment of an
22 industry-recognized credential requiring more than 100 hours of training.
23 (6) One thousand one hundred dollars ($1,100) for the attainment of a high school
24 diploma.
25 SECTION 6.10.(e) Report. – The State Board of Community Colleges, in
26 consultation with each qualifying third-party entity, shall submit an interim report by August 15,
27 2026, and a final report by August 15, 2027, to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight
28 Committee and the Fiscal Research Division on the impact of the Program, including at least the
29 following information:
30 (1) The number of participants.
31 (2) The number of credits earned by participants.
32 (3) The number of employability skills certifications issued to participants.
33 (4) The number and type of workforce credentials earned by participants.
34 (5) The number of participants who received a high school diploma.
35 (6) The average funding provided per participant who received a high school
36 diploma.
37 (7) The percentage of participants who received a high school diploma.
38 SECTION 6.10.(f) Follow-Up. – To the extent possible, the North Carolina
39 Community Colleges System Office shall attempt to collect data on employment outcomes for
40 students who participated in the Program pursuant to this section. Any data collected shall be
41 submitted to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee by July 15 of the year in which
42 the data was collected.
43 SECTION 6.10.(g) Nonreversion. – The nonrecurring funds appropriated in this act
44 for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office to
45 establish the Program pursuant to this section shall not revert at the end of the 2025-2026 fiscal
46 year but shall remain available until the end of the 2026-2027 fiscal year.
47 SECTION 6.10.(h) Administration. – Of the nonrecurring funds appropriated in this
48 act for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office for
49 the Program, the System Office shall use up to one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) to hire
50 one full-time equivalent position to administer the Program.
