18 RESPONSIBLE FATHERHOOD NORTH CAROLINA ACT
19 SECTION 7.53.(a) The General Assembly recognizes that families are stronger
20 when both parents act responsibly in caring for their children. It is the intent of the General
21 Assembly to recognize and support the important and unique role that fathers play in ensuring
22 the physical, emotional, and economic well-being of their children and families.
23 SECTION 7.53.(b) The Department shall contract for the development and
24 implementation of the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program. The program shall
25 provide an opportunity for every father in the State to be able to obtain information and
26 inspiration that will motivate and enable him to enhance his abilities as a father, recognizing that
27 some fathers have greater challenges than others and would benefit from greater support. The
28 entity the Department contracts with to develop, implement, and manage the program, "Program
29 Manager," shall be a nonprofit organization that satisfies all of the following criteria:
30 (1) Has a history of focusing on responsible fatherhood, including providing
31 online resources to fathers, and engaging fathers, father figures, and children
32 through community-based and school-based events to encourage responsible
33 fatherhood.
34 (2) Has the organizational capacity to manage a statewide initiative and
35 successfully carry out the requirements of this section.
36 SECTION 7.53.(c) The Program Manager shall be solely responsible for developing,
37 implementing, and managing the program which shall include at least the following:
38 (1) A statewide media campaign that increases the awareness and importance of
39 fathers being involved in their children's lives.
40 (2) Resources and information for fathers and father figures to increase
41 engagement and involvement in their children's lives.
42 (3) Promotion of related fatherhood programs that are provided by the
43 Department of Public Instruction, the Community College System, or The
44 University of North Carolina System.
45 SECTION 7.53.(d) To most effectively use the funds appropriated to this program,
46 the Program Manager shall identify and use other existing media assets, content, and online
47 resources it deems appropriate, including any existing media assets, content, and online resources
48 it has available, to implement and execute the items required by this section.
49 SECTION 7.53.(e) The Program Manager shall administer a grant program to award
50 grants to nonprofit community-based organizations that address the needs of fathers in
51 accordance with the following:
Page 146 Senate Bill 257-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The Program Manager shall award the following types of grants:
2 a. Grants that comprehensively address the needs of fathers, such as
3 assisting them in finding employment, managing child support
4 obligations, transitioning from a period of incarceration, accessing
5 health care, understanding child development, and enhancing
6 parenting skills. Services provided shall be tailored to the needs of the
7 father being served. Case management services shall be provided to
8 the fathers who are served by the grants under this subdivision.
9 b. Grants that provide evidence-based parenting education specifically
10 for fathers. The grants under this subdivision do not require case
11 management services.
12 (2) The Program Manager shall prioritize awarding grants according to the
13 following:
14 a. Need in a geographic area and the population to be served by the grant
15 as indicated by, at a minimum, all of the following:
16 1. Unemployment rates.
17 2. Incarceration rates.
18 3. Housing instability.
19 4. The number of single-parent households.
20 5. The number of public benefit recipients.
21 6. Graduation rates.
22 7. Levels of academic achievement.
23 b. If an applicant has a primary mission of, or a history of a significant
24 focus on and effective work toward, addressing the needs of men in
25 their role as fathers.
26 c. Applicant current and historical involvement in the community being
27 served.
28 d. Applicant commitment and capability to employ competent staff who
29 can effectively engage with the fathers being served, including, at a
30 minimum, those individuals who share a similar background as the
31 fathers being served.
32 e. The number of individuals the applicant plans to serve through the
33 grant and the projected costs for the program.
34 f. Applicant organizational capacity to effectively meet the requirements
35 of the grant and to deliver the programs proposed by the applicant. The
36 Program Manager may offer technical assistance to applicants and
37 grant recipients that have lower organizational capacity as long as such
38 organizations have, or the organization's leadership has, significant
39 experience serving fathers.
40 (3) Grant recipients shall submit reports to the Department in a format and at
41 intervals prescribed by the Department.
42 SECTION 7.53.(f) Of the funds appropriated to the Department of Public Instruction
43 in this act for the Responsible Fatherhood North Carolina program, the Department shall use up
44 to two million dollars ($2,000,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to
45 contract for the Program Manager as required in subsection (b) of this section. The remainder of
46 the funds shall be used for the grants authorized in subsection (e) of this section.
