12 MORATORIUM ON ISSUANCE OF CERTIFICATES FOR CERTAIN SURFACE
13 WATER TRANSFERS
14 SECTION 12.16.(a) Findings. – The General Assembly finds that the State's laws
15 regulating surface water transfers, originally enacted more than 30 years ago, should be
16 comprehensively reviewed and evaluated for updates in light of the State's tremendous economic
17 and population growth and the impact of natural disasters on riverine and water reservoir systems
18 over that period. In particular, the General Assembly finds that the approval of proposed transfers
19 that are significant in terms of their size compared to the overall hydrologic flow, current and
20 future water storage capacity, and cumulative water resources demands within the source river
21 basin should be temporarily paused while this review and evaluation is ongoing.
22 SECTION 12.16.(b) Study. – The North Carolina Collaboratory at the University of
23 North Carolina at Chapel Hill (Collaboratory) shall study the current statutory process for
24 approval of surface water transfers and provide any recommendations for legislation revising that
25 process that the Collaboratory finds is needed. As part of its study, the Collaboratory shall review
26 all of the following:
27 (1) The adequacy of the requirements for an environmental impact study set forth
28 in G.S. 143-215.22L(d) in ensuring that all impacts on upstream and
29 downstream users of water in the river basin are comprehensively and
30 equitably compiled and considered.
31 (2) Whether the information on which the Environmental Management
32 Commission (EMC) bases final certification decisions adequately takes into
33 account (i) issues of economic equity for lower income and lower population
34 communities in the source river basin that would experience potential impacts
35 on future economic growth due to the proposed transfer, (ii) negative impacts
36 of increases in water pollutant concentration caused by large surface water
37 transfers on riverine ecosystems, and (iii) whether the denial of the surface
38 transfer request would result in a substantial increase in utility rates or
39 otherwise cause a financial hardship due to alternative infrastructure
40 construction costs for the requesting party.
41 (3) Changes to the process needed to reflect the impact of recent climate trends
42 that impact the range of water flows in the State's mainstem rivers during
43 periods of extreme heat, drought, or flooding events.
44 (4) How to build into the certification process incentives for parties requesting
45 surface water transfers to implement land use, infrastructure, and drought
46 resiliency policies that will reduce the size of transfers needed to meet future
47 water demands.
48 (5) Any other matters the Collaboratory deems relevant to its efforts to increase
49 the fairness and effectiveness of the surface water transfer certification
50 requirements.
Page 314 Senate Bill 257-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 12.16.(c) Consultation. – In conducting the study required by subsection
2 (b) of this section, the Collaboratory will consult with the Army Corps of Engineers and other
3 private or public entities with management responsibilities over water impoundments with
4 respect to the impact of significant surface water transfers, as defined in subsection (e) of this
5 section, on those impoundments continuing to meet their present levels and future projected
6 needs for hydroelectric power generation and water supply.
7 SECTION 12.16.(d) Report. – By January 1, 2027, the Collaboratory shall report its
8 findings, along with any legislative recommendations, to the Joint Legislative Oversight
9 Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources.
10 SECTION 12.16.(e) Moratorium on Certain Surface Water Transfer Certificates. –
11 In order to permit sufficient time for the General Assembly to complete the study, the EMC shall
12 not issue a certificate authorizing a significant new surface water transfer or a significant increase
13 in an existing surface water transfer until the end of the moratorium provided in this section. The
14 moratorium in this section shall end six months after the submission of the report required by
15 subsection (d) of this section. For purposes of this section, a proposed new or increased surface
16 water transfer is significant if it would result in a total increase in transfer between river basins,
17 as defined in G.S. 143-215.22G, in excess of 15,000,000 gallons per day.
18 SECTION 12.16.(f) This section is effective when it becomes law.
